title: Federal Business Strategist
description: Mr. Kawecki currently serves as the Federal Business Strategist for ADG, providing business management leadership for the firm’s federal contracts. In this role Mr. Kawecki serves as the corporate business liaison, interacting with government and prime contractor management teams. He is responsible for providing financial data, analysis and strategic consultation to internal and client senior management teams facilitating funding and resource planning decision-making processes. He is also responsible for ensuring ADG’s federal billing process is accurate, compliant, and in alignment with federal funding source requirements. In addition, Mr. Kawecki is responsible for the development and implementation of corporate financial data collection, analysis and reporting tools and templates. In his role at ADG, Mr. Kawecki has provided business management services to contracts supporting the National Security Agency/Central Security Service (NSA/CSS), the Office of the Director of National Intelligence (ODNI), the Unites States Army (USA), the United States Air Force (USAF), the Office of Naval Intelligence (ONI), the Naval Criminal Investigative Service (NCIS), and the Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA)

title: Network Technician, Lead
description: Worked as a Tier-II help desk for the National Security Agency/Central Security Service Georgia (NSA/CSS Georgia). Created and managed Active Directory user accounts, computer accounts, security groups, distribution groups, Exchange 2003 mail accounts; created, transferred, deleted and managed permissions and groups in UNIX NIS accounts; troubleshot and maintained various site specific systems; administered and maintained Exchange servers and individual mail boxes; configured and maintained file shares and folders; backup and restored shares, folders and files; installed, configured, and upgraded software for Windows workstations on multiple networks; applied advanced diagnostic techniques to identify problems, investigated causes, and recommended solutions on desktop computers; direct line of support for the Tier1 help-desk providing training and information and help in resolving problems that cannot be resolved by Teir1 help-desk personnel; worked and resolved help requests via BMC Software and HP Service Manager (SM7); provided end-user software troubleshooting and support; provided phone and help-desk support for many local users and off-site users; worked with Administrators from other site to resolve issues; maintained current knowledge of relevant technologies as assigned.

title: Branch Chief/Help Desk
description: Supervised and led 24 employees and managed an average of 300 personnel; recommended or initiated personnel actions, such as promotions, awards, transfers, discharges, and disciplinary measures; determined schedules, and assignments for work activities based on work priority; counseled employees about work-related issues and assisted employees to correct job-skill deficiencies; conducted and arranged for employee training in safety and standard operating procedures; established and updated standard operating procedures. Managed 19 administrators of Tier II Active Directory (AD) for over 40 strategic sites across the Central Command (CENTCOM) Area of Responsibility (AOR) in the Southwest Asia-Theater of Operations and Security Center (SWA-TNOSC); directed the support of two AD structures and the migration of legacy camp domains in the SWA forest for Kuwait and Afghanistan; coordinated, planned, and deployed new systems updates, hardware and software; led the fielding of the McAfee Host Based Security System (HBSS) throughout the CENTCOM AOR; served as Joint Operation Planning and Execution (JOPES) analyst; operated the Global Command and Control System (GCCS) applications as part of the JOPES to develop and maintain requirements on the Army component Time-Phased Force Deployment Data (TPFDD) for USFK OPLANs dealing with Korean Theater of Operations; provided TPFDD products and analysis for 8th US Army staff and units as required. For 4 years trained annually over 1,900 initial entry Soldiers and foreign allies on software such as Windows Server 2003, Microsoft Exchange, Windows XP, UNIX, Solaris, and Network Security; installed, upgraded, configured, set up, troubleshot and maintained software, hardware components, and system network connectivity of 132 combined systems.

title: Intelligence Analyst
description: -TS/SCI eligible. SAP experience. Public Trust 2017. -Certified Colorado Peace Officer. -Twenty years of experience in the U.S. Navy. -Sixteen years working within the Intelligence Community. -Broad working knowledge of the National Intelligence Community operations, procedures and responsibilities. -Past working experience with various Federal Agencies and Intelligence Community personnel to include from Senior Executive policy makers to operational level personnel. -Extensive knowledge of the National Security Agency/Central Security Service (NSA/CSS) operations and procedures including governing bodies, regulations and guidelines. -Comprehensive knowledge of Joint doctrine and the relationships among the various combatant command missions and organizations as well as a knowledge of roles, missions and capabilities of United States Army, Marine Corps, Navy, Air Force, and Coast Guard, National Guard and Reserves, working experience with various military operations throughout the world, including joint operations with foreign militaries -Comprehensive knowledge of the DOD, Joint Staff and military Services vision and strategic planning documents and development processes as well as extensive knowledge of Federal Govt. organizations. -Ability to gather, assemble and analyze facts, draw conclusions, conduct strategic analysis, devise recommended solutions, and package the entire process in briefings, papers or reports suitable for senior leadership use and decision making. -Ability to perform strategic-level concept analysis and development. -Ability to perform strategic analysis of national, interagency, DOD and Joint Staff. -Strong written and oral communications. -Strong leadership skills. -Capability to work in a team environment as well as the ability to accept the responsibility to work alone. -Extensive knowledge of all Microsoft Office products as well as numerous databases and query tools.

title: USMC Enlisted and Officer
description: Enlisted as a Pvt. to Colonel. Served in numerous billets in the Communications, Signals Intelligence, Intelligence, as well as Special Operations. Worked for the National Security Agency (NSA) as the USMC Rep to the NSA/Central Security Service (NSA/CSS) and selected as a NSA/CSS Fellowship Program with follow-on as Executive Assistant to the Director, NSA/CSS. Served as the Battalion Executive and Commanding Officer of 2ND Radio Battalion. Distinguished himself and command during combat operations in Beirut, Lebanon, and operations in Central America and Grenada winning the National Security Agency/Central Security Service “Director’s Trophy” in May 1984. Served in Office of the Secretary of Defense as the USMC Rep to the Assistant Secretary of Defense, Command, Control, Communications and Intelligence (C3I), also Hq, Marine Corps as the Deputy Head and Operations Officer of the Signals Intelligence/Electronic Warfare Branch, Intelligence Division and then as the Executive Assistant to the Assistant Chief of Staff, Command, Control, Communications and Intelligence, Headquarters, USMC. Served in III Marine Expeditionary Force, Okinawa, Japan, where he formed, activated and commanded the Third Surveillance, Reconnaissance and Intelligence Group (3RD SRIG). Col Keller was Joint designated with the U.S. Atlantic Command (USLANTCOM) standing up the J-27, Director of Production and Director of Field Support as part of the Atlantic Intelligence Command (AIC). August 6, 1994 Colonel Keller was“dual hat” as Assistant Chief of Staff (G-2) for US MARFORLANT and the II Marine Expeditionary Force (MEF). Colonel Keller was retired from Active Service on Jan 1, 1997, with 38+ years of active service. Col Keller saw 3 tours of duty in Vietnam from 66-68; 69-70; and 1972 conducting Infantry, Communications, Signals Intelligence and Special Operations, including operations with 1st MARDIV, 7th Fleet, and 9th MAB while at Chu Lai, and Quảng Trị Province.

title: Program Manager
description: responsible for managing cryptologic training standards for SIGINT and Morse courses across all services and National Security Agency/Central Security Service. Managed comprehensive training standards for four operational and technical development paths at the basic, intermediate, and advanced levels of Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) analysis and Morse curricula. Coordinated and led multiple SIGINT Cryptologic Training Advisory Groups (CTAG) composed of representative/subject matter experts (SME) from all military services and NSA/CSS, for the purpose of establishing, revising, reviewing, and validating cryptologic training conducted under the auspices of an Executive Agent (EA) or Responsible Training Authority (RTA) to ensure technical adequacy. Managed the daily execution of the Cryptologic Training System (CTS) for SIGINT and Morse programs; encompassed identifying NSA/CSS and joint training requirements, designing and implementing curricula, evaluating training, and ensuring that institutional cryptologic training is accurate, current, and responsive to mission requirements of the field and tactical customers. Databases/Systems used: NSA Net, JWICS, SIPR Net, Intelink, NMCI , AMHS, MS Office (Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Access)

title: Leading Supervisor
description: Led a diverse multi-person team in the Ship’s Signals Exploitation (SSES) in support of operational, national, and Theater commander. Collected Signals intelligence (SIGINT) from various types of intelligence collection assets by utilizing state of the art collection equipment such as Digital Receiver Technology (DRT) equipment and various direction finding (DF) equipment. Analytical work focused on substantive intelligence matters involving Narco-Terrorists groups and various military targets in the Middle East, Horn of Africa, Central, and South America. Driving force behind a highly trained multi-personnel watch floor that resulted in the collection and processing of numerous signals of interest, providing 5th Fleet, Office of Naval Intelligence (ONI), and the National Security Agency/ Central Security Service (NSA/CSS) with critical information. Coordinated efforts in guiding and training personnel in Signals Intelligence collections, Combat Direction Fining (CDF) in support of National and Theater commanders. As Command Personal Qualification Standard (PQS) coordinator; assigned, monitored, and reported on the PQS completion for 240 personnel to ensure that the command maintained qualified personnel to conduct tactical operations in support of National and Theater commanders. Leading Supervisor – Joint Task Force Guantanamo (JTG-GETMO) Guantanamo Bay Cuba; As Sergeant of the Guard (SOG) supervised 89 highly trained maximum security personnel. Responsible for the day-to-day safe and humane treatment of more than 160 Global War on Terrorism detainees within the maximum confines of the maximum security facility Camp Delta. Made amazing contributions to the resounding success of opening the $37 million maximum security detention facility at camp Delta. Charged with the care of 89 highly trained detainee guards in extremely arduous conditions and effectively kept moral high. Responsible for the safe and humane detainment of over 160 enemy combatants.

title: Certified Master Training Specialist
description: Basic Communication Signals collection course instructor; led and managed numerous multi-service students and multiple staff, facilitating graduation of 32 classes with a 96% graduation rate. Managed daily administrative operations while providing guidance and direction to multi-service students and instructors of the Cryptologic Signals Collection and Processing course (CSCPC). Delivered 1356 hours of instruction to five classes, providing the technical skill paramount in supporting National operations and Theater commanders. Monitored and tracked over 200 tests for 25 multi-service instructors to further enhance their technical knowledge. Used accumulated test data to revamp p the divisional testing plan, substantially reducing the attrition rate for Cryptologic Technician collections operators.

title: Signals Analyst
description: Ship’s Signals Exploitation Space (SSES) signals analyst, intercepted numerous critical enemy signals of interest in support of National and Theater commanders during Operation Enduring Freedom. Work center supervisor for two major work centers with multiple personnel assigned. Led the completion of 300 preventive maintenance checks and ensured all cryptologic equipment systems were 100% operational. Coordinated 200 training classes that led to fully operational readiness work centers. Responsible for EKMS and CMS material and accountability for the transfer of highly classified cryptologic keys for adjacent cryptologic systems - responsible for the loading, operation, & maintenance of cryptologic keying, communications, & encryption equipment/devices such as CYZ-10, KYK-13, KY-15, KOI-18, KG-84A/C, STUIII, & KIV-7 Qualified basic CMS user and Cryptologic communications supervisor. Sat up and maintained cryptologic classified material library, space accreditation and tempest accreditation.

title: Signals Analyst
description: Designed collection strategies and coordinated collection efforts across the CENTCOM and SOUTHCOM areas of responsibilities (AOR). Authored numerous products on targets collected against targets of interest, which were widely disseminated across the Intelligence Community (IC) using Content Preparation Environment (CPE). title: CHIEF OF STAFF and PROGRAM MANAGER
company: National Security Agency / Central Security Service
description: Helmed the NSA’s cross-disciplinary, culturally diverse team, spanning locations across Europe and providing linguistic and Intelligence services in support of US national security. Meticulously managed and monitored the multi-million dollar annual budget to ensure adequate funds for facility maintenance and expansion, equipment, and staffing in support of operations. HUMAN CAPITAL / TEAM MANAGEMENT:  Optimized performance of NSA organizational functions: security, logistics, training, and IT for 26 national-level missions.  Identified critical personnel gaps and recruited/hired key staff to enhance organizational capabilities, including budget, IT, security, facility management, and administrative personnel. Assembled an outcome-oriented team that flexed with fluid environments, excelled at partnering with foreign nationals, and met challenging national and international goals.  Served as the focal point during 2011 NSA Joint Inspector General (IG) visit. Established critical IG access to personnel, processes, and functional areas to enable in-depth timely analysis of organizational functions and performance. Publicly recognized by Joint IG team's senior leadership for outstanding performance. Visionary and solution-focused strategist and team leader with more than 25 years of proven successes managing medium-to-large organizations, small/large cross-functional teams, and complex, multi-faceted projects. Cradle-to-grave oversight of multi-million dollar programs and projects while accelerating employee performance and driving timely, top-quality results despite massive obstacles, including austere environments, rigid cultural barriers, aggressive timelines, and continuously fluctuating budgets. Change architect, skilled at realigning organizations for optimal outcomes, and applying dynamic organizational skills to promote process improvements and team excellence.

title: DIRECTOR OF INTELLIGENCE
company: NATO Training Mission and Combined Security Transition Command - Afghanistan
description: Directed a joint military service operational Intelligence organization during continuous combat linked to Operation ENDURING FREEDOM. Led a versatile team, including Intelligence personnel and 1,400 linguists supporting NATO’s training mission, which seeks to prepare Afghan National Security Forces (ANSF) for full security responsibilities countrywide. PROJECT MANAGEMENT:  Coordinated the delivery of critical Intelligence data to a geographically dispersed military force, including 16 General Officers. Actively supported maturation of the Afghan Intelligence Community, promoting future transfer of responsibilities.  Subject Matter Expert in developing, training, equipping, and mentoring ANSF Intelligence leaders and organizations. Advanced and actively managed combined projects exceeding $250M that included Intelligence Mobile Training Teams, Unmanned Aerial Systems, Aerostats (unmanned surveillance balloons), and a National Military Intelligence Center.

title: MILITARY INTELLIGENCE HR SYSTEMS STAFF MANAGER
company: Department of the Army G1, Human Resource Development
description: Directed an Army HR functional area engaged in analyzing Army Intelligence human resources and building plans and programs to respond to evolving personnel needs for Military Intelligence Branch, Foreign Area Officers, Information Operations, and Interpreter/Translators. HUMAN CAPITAL / TEAM MANAGEMENT:  Conducted extensive HR planning and analysis to build plans and initiatives for the new US Army Cyber Command, the Army’s locus for issues involving cyberspace and information operations. Served in a pivotal role on the Cyber Tiger Team, predicting future staffing requirements and structure for the design of ARMY CYBER. Provided current staffing authorizations and applied quantitative strategies, such as predictive analysis, to determine the Army’s investment in the future Cyber force.  Implemented sweeping HR changes via redesign, shaping, and pioneering staffing methods for multiple Army organizational units to build efficiencies and performance throughout the Continental US (CONUS) and Europe.  Engineered new HR policies affecting Military Intelligence, Information Operations, and Foreign Area Officer staffing, contributing to Department of Defense savings of more than $4B.

title: European Command and Africa Command Collections Branch Chief
description: As an Intelligence expert, mentored and coordinated an elite joint military, all-source Intelligence collection team that supported major military commands based worldwide. Provided timely, focused Intelligence efforts in support of Department of Defense analysts, senior policy makers, and executive military leadership. TEAM LEADERSHIP / PROJECT MANAGEMENT:  Developed and presented daily intelligence updates to the US Under Secretary of Defense for Intelligence, informing critical decisions at national and international levels regarding NATO-related intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance assignments. Resulting decisions shaped operations on the ground in Kosovo, Turkey, the Levant, and Afghanistan.  Led an Intelligence team in collecting critical information relevant to Operation BURNT FROST, the controversial “shoot down” of a classified US satellite. Team efforts publically cited by DIA at an Agency-wide recognition.

title: Senior SIGINT Analyst (Linguist)
company: Senior Cryptologic Linguist, 75th Ranger Regiment, Ft Benning, GA
description: 2009-2011 Senior Cryptologic Linguist, 75th Ranger Regiment, Ft Benning, GA Senior Cryptologic SIGINT Linguist for a globally deployable tactical Operational SIGINT Team (OST) which conducts Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) and Electronic Warfare (EW) operations in support of the 75th Ranger Regiment Special Troops Battalion and the three Ranger Line Battalions; responsible for exploitation and analysis of communication devices; which conducts SIGINT/EW and radio reconnaissance operations in denied, hostile, and politically sensitive areas; responsible for all linguistic duties for languages in Central and South America; responsible for operational training for the CENTCOM areas of Operations. - Received Army impact award for numerous Tactical combat Operation. - Produced numerous SIGINT reports in response to Request for information from Task Force personnel resulting in the detainment of numerous High Value Targets. - Led SIGINT Team in numerous tactical Objectives who... - Worked as the Geospatial SIGINT Analyst Exploitation NCOIC for a Tactical Screening Facility; CELLEX, DOCEX section. - Conducted Task Force SIGINT daily briefings, Analysis, Target Development, Tactical equipment training, and Mission Support during tactical deployment during Operation Enduring Freedom (OEF).

company: Senior SINGT Analyst, 314st Military Intelligence NSA/CSS Texas, Lackland AFB, TX
description: 2006-2009 Senior SINGT Analyst, 314st Military Intelligence NSA/CSS Texas, Lackland AFB, TX Analyst Leader responsible for the accountability, training and professional development of an eight member Analyst Team; Senior SIGINT Analyst responsible for the daily processing of numerous time sensitive transmission in support of national-level priorities in the Western Hemisphere; employs expert technical knowledge in preparing target packages; supports operations in support of Force Protection Operations; lead trainer and target developer for different target set; provides direct input for operational and strategic planning, programming, and recommendations for optimal production within areas of operations. - Trained joint service and civilian linguists in Special Intelligence Processing Applications; resulted in a weekly production increase of over 30%. - Exceeded NSA/CSS mission standard of 80% by scoring 98% on mission certification test.

title: Sergeant/Team Leader
description: -NSA Menwith Hill, Harrogate, England. Sept, 07 – Nov, 09 Expert on 3 separate NSA operation’s floor systems. Supervised and evaluated up to 20 employees. Successfully completed courses in analysis, DEPL and NETA. -Analyst for Signals Support Team, Iraq. Jan, 09 – Jul, 09 Lead a team of analysts responsible for 2nd Brigade’s, a hostile and target dense area of responsibility. Constructed 52 Microsoft Power Point presentations consisting of the analysis on high value targets. Disseminated 10 tactical reports and answered over 50 time-sensitive Requests for Information to tactical and strategic level planners, directly impacting combat actions against foreign insurgents. Platoon Sergeant, Intelligence Course Instructor, and Evaluator. November, 09 – February, 2012 Instructed over 31 tactical SIGINT training courses while simultaneously coordinating with NSA appointed instructor; meanwhile, maintaining responsibility for evaluating their performance, effort, and SIGINT Tactical knowledge. Instructed over 22 analysis of SIGINT training courses while simultaneously coordinating with NSA appointed instructors; meanwhile, evaluating performance, effort, and SIGINT Analysis knowledge. Performed under pressure for 13 field training exercises in Team Leader position for both tactical and analytical SIGINT operations. -Team Leader for Tactical SIGINT Operations, Afghanistan. Aug, 2010 – Feb, 2011 Lead a team of 5 Marines for Tactical SIGINT operations in aid of Marine Corps Infantry. Allocated, accountable for, and used $2.5M in tactical signals collection equipment. Created a tracking spreadsheet of over 300 targets in Microsoft Excel in a period of six months. Reduced casualty rates by 90% with over 2,000 time sensitive of indication and warning intelligence reports. Aided supported unit with tight SIGINT deadlines, intelligence interrogations, SIGINT tactical jamming, direction finding, tactical atmospheric reporting, and over 50 SIGINT aided combat patrols.

title: Apple Care Advisor
description: Apple is products and it's people: As an "Apple At-Home Advisor", I worked to support many of Apple's popular products. As the customers’ first point of contact, I became the friendly voice of Apple, providing award-winning customer service, troubleshooting, and support. I listened to customers and used technical expertise, creativity, and passion to meet their needs — and remind them that behind Apple's great products are amazing people. I also collected information and saved data on every call record. My help desk experience included working independently from home in both phone and in online chat help queues, and in rapidly learning from developing trends and changes in the market to get the most up to date information to our customers. My highest achievement was maintaining a position in the top 100 employees on the metrics leaderboards.

title: Security
description: As a security officer at the Kahala Mall and Kahala Office Towers, I was responsible for basic patrol duties, customer service and care, asset protection, daily report writing, and rules enforcement for the public and non-common areas of the mall. As a security officer I was a direct representation of both my security agency and my client business's policies and professionalism. It is a security officer's duty to make the patrons of these patrolled locations feel safe and protected, and to assist those in need who request assistance. Additionally I was required to keep meticulous records on day to day operations, data, information passed down from local authorities, and instructions from superiors or clients.

title: National/Tactical Systems Integration
description: • Led Multi-source Intelligence System Development: Identified next-generation multi-source intelligence capabilities that satisfied national and fleet requirements for intelligence collection, processing and dissemination. Represented FLTCYBERCOM and OPNAV Military Intelligence Program (MIP) cryptologic systems requirements to NSA.

title: SENIOR BUDGET ANALYST
description: Dr. Cutler’s expertise includes supporting the development and coordination of the Program Objective Memorandum (POM) and Intelligence POM (IPOM), supporting DOD’s Planning, Programming, Budgeting, and Execution (PPBE) and Intelligence Planning, Programming, Budgeting, and Evaluation (IPPBE) cycles, and developing and coordinating inputs to the Congressional Justification Book (CJB) and Congressional Budget Justification Book (CBJB). He is a subject matter expert that identifies resource requirements including cost estimating and financial planning & reporting. Dr. Cutler creates spend plans while tracking expenditure rates, resource allocations, and budget statuses, resulting in the reconciliation of millions of dollars in unliquidated obligations. Additionally, he prepares purchase requests, execute budgets, and develop Military Interdepartmental Purchase Requests (MIPRs) and other interagency agreements.

Efforts guaranteed travel discrepancies were upheld below the 2% CITIBANK delinquency rate. - Superb Manager. Meticulously managed 130 items worth $92K across 5 departments via 4 inventories. Achieved 100% accountability with zero discrepancies, ensuring 100% compliance with 10th FLEET standards and Department of Defense instructions. Engaging leader who values mission successes and personnel development. UNQUESTIONABLY, a MULTIFACETED individual who is equipped to EXCEL within the CIVILIAN SECTOR that encompasses a VAST knowledge in business practices, cost analysis and procurement acquisitions!

description: FISCAL OFFICER/COMPTROLLER Focused, results-driven Logistics, Supply, and Finance professional with 20 years of experience and reputation for consistently meeting the most challenging organizational goals and objectives with unequaled success. Proven and verifiable record of producing higher performance standards and enhancing productivity with diverse personnel. Able to motivate team members and maximize productivity and morale without financial incentives. Consistently demonstrates the ability to develop and implement highly successful short and long-term strategic plans, routinely completes projects on time even during governmental financial constraints. Active participant in the U.S. Navy upper-level management team that proved that the military could be managed like a well-tuned corporate machine by efficiently managing complex organizations, supervising hundreds of personnel through many line-management personnel, and responsible for maintaining a 20 year Naval career cumulative monetary budget of $280 million in support of (4) U.S. Naval combatant ships, (78) F/A-18 attack fighter aircaft, and mission critical equipment in support of National Security Overseas Contingency Operations.

title: USS THE SULLIVANS, STORES DIVISION and EDUCATIONAL SERVICES OFFICER
description: Responsible for day-to-day shipboard OPTAR with annual budget of over $3.5M; Led command’s Depot Level Repairable/Maintenance Assistance Module inventories to receive 100% validity. Leadership ensured unit to be awarded the Navy “E” 2002 & 2003; Coordinated re-construction of the command HAZMAT program. Assisted NAVSUP with inventory of $54K of HAZMAT and offload of $15K of expired HAZMAT and GUCL material trimming the oversized program by 25%; Assigned as command C5RA and HMERA supply department liaison. Responsible for short-fused procurement of 413 requisitions valued at over $239K; Command Educational Services Officer who established and coordinated PACE and Distant Learning programs for unit. Ensured 300 sailors had opportunity to attend college while on 2004 deployment.

title: CHIEF OF STAFF and PROGRAM MANAGER
company: National Security Agency / Central Security Service
description: Helmed the NSA’s cross-disciplinary, culturally diverse team, spanning locations across Europe and providing linguistic and Intelligence services in support of US national security. Meticulously managed and monitored the multi-million dollar annual budget to ensure adequate funds for facility maintenance and expansion, equipment, and staffing in support of operations. HUMAN CAPITAL / TEAM MANAGEMENT:  Optimized performance of NSA organizational functions: security, logistics, training, and IT for 26 national-level missions.  Identified critical personnel gaps and recruited/hired key staff to enhance organizational capabilities, including budget, IT, security, facility management, and administrative personnel. Assembled an outcome-oriented team that flexed with fluid environments, excelled at partnering with foreign nationals, and met challenging national and international goals.  Served as the focal point during 2011 NSA Joint Inspector General (IG) visit. Established critical IG access to personnel, processes, and functional areas to enable in-depth timely analysis of organizational functions and performance. Publicly recognized by Joint IG team's senior leadership for outstanding performance. Visionary and solution-focused strategist and team leader with more than 25 years of proven successes managing medium-to-large organizations, small/large cross-functional teams, and complex, multi-faceted projects. Cradle-to-grave oversight of multi-million dollar programs and projects while accelerating employee performance and driving timely, top-quality results despite massive obstacles, including austere environments, rigid cultural barriers, aggressive timelines, and continuously fluctuating budgets. Change architect, skilled at realigning organizations for optimal outcomes, and applying dynamic organizational skills to promote process improvements and team excellence.

Provided timely, focused Intelligence efforts in support of Department of Defense analysts, senior policy makers, and executive military leadership. TEAM LEADERSHIP / PROJECT MANAGEMENT:  Developed and presented daily intelligence updates to the US Under Secretary of Defense for Intelligence, informing critical decisions at national and international levels regarding NATO-related intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance assignments. Resulting decisions shaped operations on the ground in Kosovo, Turkey, the Levant, and Afghanistan.  Led an Intelligence team in collecting critical information relevant to Operation BURNT FROST, the controversial “shoot down” of a classified US satellite. Team efforts publically cited by DIA at an Agency-wide recognition.

title: DEPUTY INTELLIGENCE MANAGER
description: Coordinated and oversaw the delivery of current Intelligence to the Commanding General and other senior military leaders. Provided comprehensive operational and administrative leadership for various Intelligence elements, including Planning, Operations, Analysis and Control, Weather Office, and the Terrain Detachment. Adroitly managed the Intelligence budget (~$4M), and fostered high team performance with team-building initiatives. HR LEADERSHIP / ADMINISTRATIVE LEADERSHIP:  Orchestrated distribution of Intelligence staff, conducting strategic planning to ensure well-placed, highly qualified personnel to meet immediate and long-range needs for intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance (ISR) activities.  Deftly refocused Intelligence section leaders and line personnel following their return from Operation IRAQI FREEDOM, ensuring a smooth segue from combat environments to preparations for future contingency operations.  Rebuilt HR systems to promote reintegration and retraining for these combat veterans while simultaneously grooming new generations of leaders with appropriate professional development and mentoring.

Created a tracking spreadsheet of over 300 targets in Microsoft Excel in a period of six months. Reduced casualty rates by 90% with over 2,000 time sensitive of indication and warning intelligence reports. Aided supported unit with tight SIGINT deadlines, intelligence interrogations, SIGINT tactical jamming, direction finding, tactical atmospheric reporting, and over 50 SIGINT aided combat patrols.

title: SENIOR SALES EXECUTIVE
description: Responsible for generating new business revenue. Provide ongoing security solutions to existing customers. This position reported to the SVP of Sales. KEY ACHIEVEMENTS: Produced on average 150% over quota revenue achievement, instrumental in company’s 20% quarter-over-quarter revenue growth and subsequent Initial Public Offering in 2001 that raised $52 million. Awarded Top Sales Executive company-wide for Q2 CY’00, recognized for outperforming peers. Consistently exceeded quota, finished as the #2 Sales Executive in the company for FY 2002. Forged license agreements with Fortune 500 companies and new start ups from diverse industries including competitive wins with Handspring, Verizon Communications, Borland Software, Verizon Wireless, Digital Island, Qualcomm, Iomega, Voyager Systems, GRIC Comm., Alteon Web Systems. Closed multi-year lucrative OEM contracts with a leading telecommunications customer under intense market pressures, total revenue generated by the combined contracts exceed several million. INDUSTRY EXPERTISE: Expertise with security software solutions for the requirements of wired and wireless data communications OEMs. Experienced with Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) management tools and certificate services. Well versed in vertical markets such as handheld devices, middleware, cable/broadband, 802.11, telecommunications and security appliances. Experienced with Enterprise Sales involving IPSec software client for VPN security and strong PDA data encryption.

title: Team Chief/ Technical Team Manager
description: Team leader in charge of a team of 7 people conducting COMINT and Geospatial SIGINT to produce timely reports for clients. Squad leader in the Army outside of the analytical shop. 2009 senior analyst and report writer for my watch during the national crisis. SME of mission crucial database and managed a team of five for technical database oversight and management of reports for the entire 50 joint forces shop. Created a homepage and multiple working aids to instruct others to optimize work output and to perform their duties correctly. Lead a team of joint service personnel; ensured tasks were evenly delegated and that each individual knew what was expected of them and worked directly with each person to make sure they knew how they could approach the project or task to achieve the most thorough result. Conducted on the job training that enabled individuals to pass their job qualification tests. Trained my replacement team leader well in advance of my departure to make sure he had the skills and confidence to perform his duties. Attended meetings and communicated regularly with peer and senior level leadership to make sure the team was supporting the mission accurately and in a timely and relevant manner up to the General level. Subject matter expert of mission crucial database; ensuring the quality of all new posts to the database and routine queries of previously entered data that was entered incorrectly. Tertiary responsibilities included managing incoming reports for the shop along with ensuring that all new reports are properly parsed to the appropriate teams. Responsible for informing the shop of all needed database current down time and predicted up times and gathering requests from the end user, interoperating those requesting into actionable tasks for the software development team.

title: Intelligence Analyst
description: • Served as an Intelligence Analyst on a U.S. Government counterterrorism program • Performed research and analysis on data and write reports, adhering to tight time lines and strict quality guidelines, using numerous U.S. Government databases with emphasis on Human Intelligence (HUMINT) and Signal Development (SIGDEV). • Was responsible for the analysis and validation of a wide variety of information which supports several facets of U.S. Government counterterrorism programs and contributes to information on potential terrorist threats. • Disseminated new reports to Intelligence and Law Enforcement communities using multiple communication nodes. • Performed basic, preliminary assessments on cyber incidents as they come to the attention watch desk in order to prioritize and properly administer them. • Performed both open- and closed-source research which consisted of locating and collating unclassified information on a specific topic or person/group that is made available by individuals or corporate entities for general or specific consumers. • Provided analytical support to augment field monitoring activities, critical technical collection and the development of preliminary analytical conclusions. • Collaborated with Cyber analysts in order to ensure accuracy of information at hand and verification of collection of the multi-sourced intelligence for exploitation opportunities. • Monitored multiple communications nodes for updates concerning previously reported threats, incidents, and advisories.

title: Language Analyst/Interpreter/Transcriber/Program Manager
description: • Transcribed all-source language materials; performed research and target analysis of research and target analysis of technical foreign language material. • Coordinated with senior analysts and subject matter experts to determine potential intelligence value and set handling priorities. • Provided direct language support and first-look analysis of targets (SIGDEV); recommended items for further collection and exploitation. • Monitor multiple communications nodes (multiple network-based computer notification and information sharing applications; multiple telephonic communications circuits; other inter- and intra-agency communications systems) for reports concerning cyber-centric threats and advisories. • Chosen above higher-ranking peers to serve as Company-level Administrative NCO, managing over 150 Soldiers, as well as office Noncommissioned Officer in Charge (NCOIC) over a team of four Soldiers. • Chosen above higher-ranking peers to serve as the Army Program Manager for the Military Language Analyst Program (MLAP). Team Leadership • Managed and advised the career development path of over 30 Language Analysts while motivating and sustaining strong focus and high expectations for performance by recommending specific National Cryptologic School courses needed to fulfill the job qualification requirements. • Briefed program to incoming personnel and higher ranking officials in order to promote the program and to get awareness to different military units world-wide, while explaining how the program is beneficial to those who would also be eventually separating from the military.

title: Brigade S2
description: Brigade S2 of an Engineer Brigade with worldwide deployment responsibilities in support of Corps, Division, and Joint operations. Responsible for providing and synchronizing all intelligence requirements providing support to over 1900 Soldiers in one engineer battalion, one chemical battalion and an EOD battalion. Leads a section of 3 Officers, 1 WO, 2 SNCOs; 4 NCOs, and 4 Soldiers in intelligence operations, Geospatial Terrain Analysis, fusion, Open Source Intelligence, and Security Operations. Determines intelligence requirements, plans intelligence collection, analyzes information, synthesizes multi-disciplinary intelligence, creates Geospatial Terrain products and disseminates intelligence to commanders in support of Brigade and Battalion operations in support of CONUS and OCONUS missions and exercises. Primary advisor to the BDE Commander and Staff on Intelligence. Advises Brigade Commander on the enemy and civilian situation and security issues. Serves as the Brigade Personnel/Information/Physical Security Manager, Brigade Provost Marshal Officer, Brigade Anti-Terrorism Officer and oversees the Intelligence Oversight Program.

title: Major
description: The Army's Military Intelligence (MI) is responsible for all intelligence gathered or learned during Army missions. MI Officers are always out front, providing essential intelligence and in many cases saving Soldiers who are fighting on the front lines. Military Intelligence Officers also assess risks associated with friendly and enemy courses of action and act to counter or neutralize identified intelligence threats. The MI Officer also uses intelligence systems and data to reduce uncertainty of enemy, terrain and weather conditions for a commander. Military Intelligence Officer provides the commander with all-source intelligence assessments and estimates at the tactical, operational, and strategic levels dealing with enemy capabilities, intentions, vulnerabilities, effects of terrain and weather on operations, and predicts enemy courses of action. Directs tasking of intelligence collection assets; produces threat estimates to support doctrine, training; and combat developments; ensures proper dissemination of intelligence information and products; manages interrogation operations of enemy prisoners of war and line crossers; interprets imagery from overhead and other systems; directs counterintelligence and operational security operations; performs clandestine human intelligence operations and manages signals intelligence operations including jamming and participating in performing deception operations. Manages these tasks at all echelons.

title: Division Intelligence Planner
description: Served as the Intelligence Planner within G5 Plans Section for the 7th Infantry Division. Responsible for developing, coordinating, synchronizing, and publishing operational orders and plans for the Division. Develop, execute, and monitor operational and joint planning groups ensuring all plans integrate and synchronize lethal and non-lethal effects at the operational and tactical level. Leverage and incorporate warfighting functional planners and components into the planning process. Coordinate plans with higher, adjacent and subordinate commands, staff sections and operations centers to facilitate concurrent and parallel planning and smooth transition to current operations. Coordinate daily planning actions and requirements as directed by the Division leaders to ensure all Division mission requirements are met according to planning standards and timelines.

title: Deputy Brigade S3, Training
description: Served as the Deputy Brigade S3 for Training for a 1,500 Soldier and civilian forward based theater Military Intelligence Brigade consisting of four subordinate MI battalions, which provide intelligence support to Army and Joint Forces in the European and African Command areas of responsibility; responsible for organizing, maintaining and preparing Training Guidance, as well as various Training and Readiness Briefings, including the Training Management Review to US Army Europe; provides oversight to individual and leader training, including the Noncommissioned Officer Education System and Foundry programs; responsible for advising, planning, coordinating and supervising operations and training events in support of Theater Security and International Security Cooperation efforts; provides oversight to the Brigade’s Ammunition Management program; synchronizes the efforts of 66th Military Intelligence Brigade's resources through USAREUR to INSCOM; provides oversight for the Brigade's Language Learning Center operations; assists in oversight of the training, morale, and welfare of 29 Soldiers and 8 Civilians within the Brigade S3 section.

title: Deputy Chief of Analysis and Productions
description: Directed Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) operations conducted at the European Cryptologic Center (ECC) - a joint cryptologic organization comprised of 270 military and civilian personnel. Conducts planning, implements guidance, and prioritizes internal resources. Answers intelligence requirements from the U.S. European Command (EUCOM), U.S. Africa Command (AFRICOM) and from other customers throughout the U.S. Government, its allies and foreign partners. Ensures collaboration between national and tactical analysts for signals intelligence mission coverage. Implements short and long term objectives that improve ECC's support to AFRICOM, EUCOM, NSA, National Security Agency / Central Security Service Europe / Africa (NCEUR/AF) and other theater and national elements as required. Duty performed as joint assignment within the Analysis and Production (S2) Directorate of NCEUR.

title: Basra Operations Command Primary Intelligence Advisor
description: Senior Intelligence Advisor for the J2, a Staff Brigadier General and the J2 Staff, at the Basra Operations Command, Basra, Iraq. Supervises, trains, and mentors the Basra Operations Command MiTT intelligence section consisting of one officer, one non-commissioned officer, and one category II interpreter. Manages and coordinates the advisory effort among the J2 intelligence section and all source cell. Advises the J2 on intelligence driven operations within United States Division - South area of operations. Provides oversight of J2 personnel issues, training, intelligence, legal system, and detainee operations, to include detainee facilities. Reports intelligence information to provide the BaOC Military Transition Team, USF, and ISF intelligence situational awareness and atmospherics improving awareness of the operational environment to enhance operations of the BaOC and USD - South.

title: Division Military Transition Team Intelligence Advisor
company: 2nd Iraq Army Division Military Transition Team (MiTT)
description: Division Military Transition Team (MiTT) G2 Intelligence advisor for the 2nd Iraqi Army Division of the Iraqi Ground Forces Command in Mosul, Iraq. Manages, trains, and mentors intelligence section consisting of one officer, one non-commissioned officer, and one category II interpreter. Manages and coordinates the advisory effort among the 2 IA G2 section, ISR Company, and subordinate Brigade S2s. Advises the 2 IA G2 on intelligence driven operations within Multi-National Division - North are of operations. Provides oversight on G2 personnel issues, training, legal system, and detainee operations, to include detainee facilities. Reports intelligence information to Coalition Force intelligence organizations and enhances cooperation between CF and IA intelligence organizations. Conducts threat assessments for force protection for base operations. Conducts combat patrols vehicle CDR and convoy CDR.

title: Signals Intelligence Analyst
description: Hand-picked amongst peers to supervise and train a team of six multi-service analysts to scan known and unknown frequencies to find a new transmission method being used by a target for undetected communications. Qualified as Enlisted Information Dominance Warfare Specialist and subject matter expert, created three documents compiling specific target knowledge and signals analysis tools to reduce reporting time by 80%. Spearheaded the innovative environmental search of the high-frequency spectrum and directed search methods to locate, process, and break out signals of interest to report on valuable intelligence in support of the U.S. Pacific Command. Skillful with multiple SIGINT intelligence applications, software and analyst tools including Pidgin, NSAnet, Secret Internet Protocol Router Network (SIPRNET), and open source information discovery methods. Conducted seventeen high priority SIGINT operations briefings at NSA and Intelligence Community field sites to target customers and special unit offices to expand geographic knowledge and advanced collection methods. Led the collaboration of two intelligence operations sites for new automated collection systems resulted in gathering 20,000 signals of interest and 840 special interest reports. Collected, processed, and analyzed over 31,800 SIGINT product reports providing situational awareness for units in the Pacific Area of Responsibility which greatly resulted in nearly 500 special interest reports. Maintained five multi-million dollar remote collection systems to ensure quick validation, time-sensitive reporting, and accurate geo-location in support of the U.S. pacific fleet area of responsibility. Analyzed time-critical intelligence information and produced SIGINT Threat Warning reports in support of U.S. assets in the assigned AOR. Tools used: Gale-Lite, Google Earth, Intelink, KLs, Oilstock, Intellipedia, and USSID System.

title: Battalion Operations Noncommissioned Officer in Charge

title: Special Operations Team-Alpha (SOT-A) Team Member/Voice Interceptor
description: Served as a Voice Interceptor on a four man Special Operations Team-Alpha (SOT-A) team in support of 7th Special Forces Group which is oriented toward Central and South America with missions in Operation Enduring Freedom; executed counter-narcotics and counter-terrorist SIGINT missions in support of real-world operations in hostile and denied environments; employed portable collection equipment in overt, covert, urban, and tactical environments; performed initial processing of time-sensitive reports of actionable intelligence; provided individual and team training. Trained on Digital Receiver Technology (DRT) Systems, AN/PSC-5C Shadowfire, and various SIGINT collection systems; Completed three months of structured Spanish Language training to better augment his team's necessary skill set; completed 20K ruck march with 55lbs in three hours and 25 minutes During entire tour recieved an AAM Impact award and an AAM for PCS Award. Also, earned the Irish Parachutist Wings Foriegn Badge.

title: Electronic Warfare Technician
description: Electronic Warfare Technicians (EWs) operate and conduct preventive maintenance on computer-controlled electronic equipment used for detection, analysis, and identification of radar emissions. They operate systems that produce high-power electronic signals used to deceive and jam enemy electronic sensors, including those associated with electronically guided weapons. EWs are responsible for interpreting incoming electronic signals to determine their source and location. They utilize computer databases to analyze the electronic intelligence they receive, allowing them to evaluate weapon and detection system capabilities and limitations. The duties performed by EWs include: operating electronic detection and deception systems; evaluating intercepted radar emissions using computer databases to determine whether emissions originate from land based, surface ship, or airborne platforms; performing technical analysis of radar signals and systems in support of technical reports used by national level agencies plotting intercepted signals to determine effective defensive maneuvers in case of attack; tracking surface and airborne targets; defending the ship against inbound threats including anti-ship missiles; Routinely working with classified information and technical material in support of national security.

title: Criminal Justice/Legal Studies Instructor
description: Legal Studies/Criminal Justice Instructor. • Instruct classes in sizes ranging from an individual to in excess of 30 students, produce lesson plans, develop syllabi, produce PowerPoint presentations, construct examinations, grade examinations, record and maintain computerized records of attendance and student performance, mentor and tutor students, and employ facilitative and student centered teaching methods. Online instructor for recorded video presentations on criminal justice topics and trainings. Carry out continuous personal development to maintain current knowledge of best practices and developing technologies in law enforcement and criminal justice. • Classes taught include Criminal Procedure, Police Operations, Terrorism Today, Introduction to Criminal Justice, Introduction to Corrections, Critical Issues in Corrections, White Collar Crime, History of Criminal Justice, Criminal Evidence, Juvenile Justice Systems, Criminology, Juvenile Delinquency, Criminal Investigation, Academic Strategies, and Criminal Law for Criminal Justice.

title: Police Officer/Detective
description: • Patrol experience- conducted preliminary investigations and prepared field reports, responded to high volume of 911 calls for service, traffic enforcement, community policing, prepared arrest and search and seizure warrants, conducted surveillance and investigations. Performed criminal and accident investigations, testified at District/Circuit/ Federal Courts/Grand Jury presentations. • Master Field Training Officer – conducted training and evaluated police trainees in patrol techniques, report writing, investigations, firearms usage and discipline, arrest procedures, crime scene preservation, community policing, driving skills and tactics, interviewing and interrogation methods, Developed new field training program utilizing court tested standards. Developed written and oral testing for Field Training Officer (FTO) candidates, assisted in developing program curriculum and standards. • Detective (Internal Affairs) - investigated allegations of police brutality, police discourtesy, neglect of duty, Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) and discrimination complaints, and violations of general orders and procedures. • C.I.D. title: WebTAS Field Engineer / Intelligence Analyst
description: Performed, coordinated, and trained data mining and analysis of data from multiple intelligence and operations data sources in support of Joint Improvised Explosive Device Defeat Organization Knowledge and Information Fusion Exchange (JKnIFE). Established mission-critical research and data-mining standards and methodologies to include multinational and multiagency data. Implemented, integrated, and trained WebTAS as the premier software suite for data mining and complex analysis. Performed all installation and configuration of WebTAS on end-user workstations as well as workstation-specific configurations via both local and remote desktop administration. Established and maintained SQL database for WebTAS user access controls, rights, permissions, and analytical information. Used Agile software development methods to engender collaboration, planning, development, testing, and delivery in an innovative, highly experimental environment for software and hardware architecture, design, and data management changes and policies which led to 2007 InfoWorld 100 Award for Innovative Technical Methods. Operated independently as sole representative of ISS, Inc on-site with no direct supervision.

title: Police Officer/Detective
description: • Patrol experience- conducted preliminary investigations and prepared field reports, responded to high volume of 911 calls for service, traffic enforcement, community policing, prepared arrest and search and seizure warrants, conducted surveillance and investigations. Performed criminal and accident investigations, testified at District/Circuit/ Federal Courts/Grand Jury presentations. • Master Field Training Officer – conducted training and evaluated police trainees in patrol techniques, report writing, investigations, firearms usage and discipline, arrest procedures, crime scene preservation, community policing, driving skills and tactics, interviewing and interrogation methods, Developed new field training program utilizing court tested standards. Developed written and oral testing for Field Training Officer (FTO) candidates, assisted in developing program curriculum and standards. • Detective (Internal Affairs) - investigated allegations of police brutality, police discourtesy, neglect of duty, Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) and discrimination complaints, and violations of general orders and procedures. • C.I.D. description: Operated in support of the USARPAC Asia-Pacific Irregular Warfare Analysis Center and the Asia-Pacific Counter-IED Fusion Center. Operated independently as sole representative of ISS, Inc on-site with no direct supervision.

title: WebTAS Field Engineer / Intelligence Analyst
description: Performed, coordinated, and trained data mining and analysis of data from multiple intelligence and operations data sources in support of Joint Improvised Explosive Device Defeat Organization Knowledge and Information Fusion Exchange (JKnIFE). Established mission-critical research and data-mining standards and methodologies to include multinational and multiagency data. Implemented, integrated, and trained WebTAS as the premier software suite for data mining and complex analysis. Performed all installation and configuration of WebTAS on end-user workstations as well as workstation-specific configurations via both local and remote desktop administration. Established and maintained SQL database for WebTAS user access controls, rights, permissions, and analytical information. Used Agile software development methods to engender collaboration, planning, development, testing, and delivery in an innovative, highly experimental environment for software and hardware architecture, design, and data management changes and policies which led to 2007 InfoWorld 100 Award for Innovative Technical Methods. Operated independently as sole representative of ISS, Inc on-site with no direct supervision.

title: Intelligence Analyst
description: Supervised, coordinated, and participated in the analysis, processing, and distribution of strategic and tactical intelligence. Directed and managed overall administration and operations for the 54th Engineer Battalion Intelligence Office. Held full responsibility for managing multi-million dollar equipment and inventory. Conducted ongoing analyses to evaluate the efficiency and quality of operations. Established and maintained a systematic, cross-referenced intelligence records and files. Determined significance and reliability of incoming information and assisted in integrating incoming information with current intelligence holdings. Overhauled and managed the implementation and maintenance of physical and personnel security requirements. Managed multiple Human Resources responsibilities including personnel, training, and development operations. Forecasted and coordinated manpower planning to meet operational requirements. Determined appropriate staffing and employee skill levels, realigned workflows to optimize productivity, and administered employee record-keeping and documentation. Established training and professional development activities that were aligned with mission, strategy, and tactical planning. Fully accountable for personnel scheduling, job assignments, disciplinary actions, performances reviews, terminations, and daily supervision.

title: AFCYBER Network Operations Controller
description: - Executed command & control (C2) of Air Force Information Network (AFIN) in accordance with Combatant Command (COCOM) and Air Force Cyber Command (AFCYBER) operational orders/directives/policies - Monitored cyber orders; ensured AFIN is protected, defended, & survivable -- guaranteed bombs on adversaries - Coordinated AFIN 24/7 active defense activities across 11 Major Commands and 323 sites - Conducted Full-Spectrum AF Cyberspace Operations in coordination with United States Cyber Command (USCC) - Supervised production/distribution of critical Cyber Command information requirement (CCIR) messages for timely 24th Air Force Commander's situational awareness - Monitored priority Unmanned Aerial Vehicle data circuits; deconflicted maintenance actions; critical to success of hundreds of Remotely Piloted Aircraft/Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (RPA/UAV) operations

title: Wing Information Assurance Officer
description: - Conducted base-wide Information Assurance assessment/assistance visits; generated reports and assisted in discrepancy identification and resolution - Trained military, civilian and contractor personnel on computer security (COMPUSEC) and IAO requirements/responsibilities - Maintained Information Assurance Officer (IAO) database, appointment letters and compliance documentation for 160+ base-wide members - Reviewed and endorsed risk analysis and designated approval authority documents prior to system accreditation on Air Force Information Network - Oversaw classified message incident reporting; guided sanitization procedures on 4 incidents shielding the $70 million network from potential compromise of sensistive data. - Identified/corrected EMSEC vulnerabilities; directed proper placement of IT devices eliminating network security incidents - Publicized key IA updates via base-wide news article -- COMPUSEC message reached 72,000 personnel; heightened situational awareness - Unit Physical Training Leader; led squadron physical training sessions to ensure unit met USAF fitness standards

title: Information Assurance Officer
description: - Managed Information Assurance (IA) programs supporting Air Force Intelligence Surveillance Reconaissance Agency (AFISRA) critical surveillance/warning mission - Performed protective/corrective security measures on 19 mission systems/3 networks ensuring 100% ISR mission sustainability - Set audit procedures; performed reviews on $480 million systems ensuring data confidentiality/availability/integrity - Ensured Information Assurance compliance of 782 users; verifies users meet security requirements prior to granting mission system access - Audited 300 weekly NSA system logs; identified/documented suspicious events--ensured 100% system integrity - Managed Group/Squadron NSA secure system mission access program; processed nine certificates--prevented unauthorized access - Maintained/managed 17 System Security Plans; approval to operate for 180 systems -- zero ISR mission disruptions - Managed Group/Squadron Sensitive Compartmented Information Facility (SCIF) accreditations; audited/recertified 450 systems in 16 SCIFs--100% compliant/approved - Managed Group/Squadron emission security (EMSEC) program; monitored 16 SCIFs/450 systems for standards/violations--100% compliance - Taught English to Republic of Korea Air Force officers; strengthened international relations and defense by enhancing communication - Unit Physical Training Leader; pushed 120 Airmen to stay fit-to-fight; improved exercise program -- Squadron PT test pass rate of 93% - Unit booster club secretary; organized/participated in $10,000 dorm gym overhaul -- raised dorm resident's quality of life

title: Command & Control Systems Administrator
description: - Directly supported Air Mobility Command mission by providing complete systems support 24 hours a day, 7 days a week - Provided 24/7 network and small computer support to three AF-UK, 100 ARW and RAF Mildenhall warfighters - Managed and supported Command and Control Information Processing System (C2IPS) and Global Decision Support System II (GDSS II) hardware and software databses valued at $1.25 million - Categorized, isolated and resolved network and computer related issues for 5,400 users - Processed, documented and resolved trouble tickets for 300+ Client Support Administrators - Ensured user availability of C2IPS applications and information for customers located at RAF Mildenhall, RAF Lakenheath, NAS Rota, Moron AB and NAS Sigonella. - Ensured user availability of GDSS II applications and information for over 13,000 customers located around the world - Coordinated all system upgrades with host base network control center and host MAJCOM - Facilitated the flow of mission critical information, supporting AMC's philosophy for command and control of all airlift and aerial refueling assest in exercises, training events and real-world operations. - Managed 155+ C2IPS user accounts ensuring the constant ability of units to schedule/track missions - Ensured timely, proper disposition of $59,000 of servicable and unservicable computer equipment to DRMO - Verified the location and validated the operability of $1.5 million of GDSS II hardware and software - Unit Physical Training Leader/Unit Fitness Program Manager; developed unit fitness program guidelines to ensure fellow airmen were fit to fight

title: Strategic Automated Command & Control System Administrator
description: - Responsible for continuous operation of the $680 million SACCS network, connecting 149 strategic Command, Control and Communication (C3) sites at 34 aircraft/missile wings and four Navy locations - Provided high-speed, multi-level secure force direction and emergency action messages (EAM) transmission capability to fielded nuclear forces on global alert. - Directly supported the POTUS, JCS, SECDEF, six Unified Commands and seven Major Commands. Provided interface to Automated Digital Network (AUTODIN), U.S. Navy's Nova communication system, Command Center Processing and Display System (CCPDS), Rapid Engagement and Combat Targeting System, and Strategic War Planning System. - Troubleshot and reported 5,500 network anomalies annually. - Delivered 83,000 messages. exceeding JCS delivery rate and proved wartime mission abilities - Researched 28 non-delivered/acknowledged Emergency Action Message (EAM) Hybrid Delivery System messages; reviewed 1,000+ pages in two hours - Alternate Squadron Fitness Manager; assisted in the AF-wide transition from 'bike-test' standard to the current '1.5 mile/pushup/situp' standard - Primary Flight Fitness Manager; led flight physical training sessions to ensure unit met USAF fitness standards - Alternate Flight Publications Monitor - Primary Flight War Book Monitor

title: Peer Mentor
description: Staffed the newly installed Veterans Center at the university, creating rules and operating procedures to ensure an effective method for assisting transitioning military veterans to integrate into the university environment. Responded to written and telephone requests for information or assistance regarding admission, enrollment, registration, financial aid, and orientation at the university for military veterans and their families. Conferred with individuals, groups and committees throughout the university and community to extend the center's program and services. Represented the student veteran community on the university's Collegiate Success for Our Troops and Their Families workgroup. Delivered written and oral presentations to various groups and individuals at the university to promote the implementation of policies important to the student veteran population, resulting in UNT being named the top military-friendly school in the state of Texas. Successfully organized the inaugural Veterans Day Celebration at the university, initiating a new university tradition.

title: Cryptologic Technician
description: Duty with the National Security Agency/Central Security Service (NSA/CSS) as a Multimode Systems operator and Block Controller assigned to the Global Response Collection and Reporting Division (GRCRD). Managed online mission collection and operators from every branch of service concerning the operation of mission systems and mentored operators on proper procedures regarding the collection of targets. Reported all special interest items to national level consumers and military intelligence commanders for use in ensuring the United States national security. Assisted subordinates and supervisors in identifying and resolving problems to ensure mission efficiency. Worked closely with other analysts to improve their reports for our respective customers. Provided personalized, tailored training to direct subordinates and assisted in the training of other personnel resulting in an overall increase in higher scores on certifications throughout the unit. Upheld a standard of excellence in personal training, seeking out new responsibilities and education at every opportunity to guarantee mission quality, consequently leading to the discovery and identification of crucial intelligence. Actively participated in the Junior Sailors Association.

title: Security Education Academic Liaison
description: The DoD assigns a Security Education Academic Liason (SEAL) representative to each of the National Centers of Academic Excellence in IA Education (CAE/IAE) and National Centers of Academic Excellence in Research (CAE-R). These representatives promote collaboration between the government and universities, define areas of mutual interest, and identify sources for research and development. Of particular interest to both is the identification of outstanding students for future government employment.

title: Chair, TEMPEST Advisory Group - Committee on National Security Systems
description: The Committee on National Security Systems (CNSS) sets national-level Information Assurance policies, directives, instructions, operational procedures, guidance and advisories for United States Government (USG) departments and agencies for the security of National Security Systems (NSS). It provides a comprehensive forum for strategic planning and operational decision-making to protect NSS and approves the release of INFOSEC products and information to Foreign Governments. Chaired US Working Group setting national policy and standards for the control of compromising emanations. Represented US TEMPEST interests on international standard bodies.

title: Senior Project Manager
company: U.S. Department of the Treasury Bureau of the Fiscal Service
description: Senior Project Manager and government representative with responsibilities for planning, integrating, evaluating, and directing the work of project resource personnel at the professional, technical, and administrative work levels. Responsible for mentoring other project managers within the Bureau of Public Debt. Handles lead project management responsibilities for technical and financial Software as a Service platforms. Majority of projects are integration of Government organizations onto Oracle Federal Financials, Compusearch Prism, Concur Electronic Travel System, and Kronos WebTA. Currently acting in a Subject Matter Expert and mentoring role for the creation of Grants Management Requirements and subsequent Request for Proposal to external Vendors. Acted in an advisory role to the Department of the Treasury and Government Wide Accounting for the refresh and replanning of the United States General Fund program. The previous initiatives had failed to produce mitigations and corrections to audit findings and major discrepancies in the United States General Fund. The current ongoing initiative was falling behind schedule and was on track to miss key milestones and result in another failed project. After performing an in-depth analysis of the project and performing a "reset" and "refresh" of the projects and program the current initiative is re-baselined and has been migrated to the Government Wide Accounting agency for execution.

title: Executive Communications Civilian Lead
description: Serves as the civilian lead and subject matter expert for all voice, video and data communications support to the AMC Commanding General and Senior Leadership. Provides technical expertise to the design, development, and implementation of information security policies and procedures. Performs supervisory role for assigned contractor work force in the roles of operations, maintenance and training for IT resources. Serves as a technical subject matter expert in the areas of systems analysis and information management planning for agency-wide support. Responsible for technical and functional planning, implementation, project management, and systems integration for a wide range of IT programs. Utilizes extensive subject matter expertise in providing customer support to end users and customers for network systems, software and virtualization technologies. Accomplishments • Led the IT infrastructure movement for the HQ AMC Commanding General and support staff from temporary facilities to permanent location. The movement of IT and communications infrastructure was completed ahead of schedule and with no degradation of IT and communications capabilities. • Led the decommissioning project for IT and communications infrastructure of the Headquarters Army Materiel Command temporary locations. The locations encompassed 16 disparate buildings and over 600 personnel and associated IT and communications equipment. The decommissioning of associated IT and communications gear was accomplished ahead of schedule with a resulting cost savings.

title: Brigade Deputy S6 (Chief Information Officer)
company: U.S. Army Materiel Command (AMC) 401st Army Field Support Brigade (AFSB)
description: Temporary Deployment (not to exceed 179 days) to serve as the acting deputy S-6 for the 401st Field Support Brigade, Bagram, Afghanistan, with a total end user population of approximately 5,500 persons. Provides subject matter expertise and guidance to the S6 and 401st Brigade on realignment and closure of sites and the corresponding processes and procedures to ensure communications resources are seamlessly transitioned. Provides subject matter expertise for review and recommendations for change of contractor workforce contracts and performance work statements. Manages subordinate government and contractor workforce activities to ensure that short and long term mission objectives are met. Communicates with subordinate battalions to ensure that the Brigade mission is being accomplished. Provides situational updates to the 401st Brigade Commander and theater signal commands through daily, weekly and monthly briefings. Coordinates with theater and higher headquarters organizations in order to ensure that all communications and information technology goals are synchronized.

title: Action Officer Defense Switched Network and Cryptographic Modernization
description: Performed the role of lead Information Technology Project Manager and government representative with responsibilities for planning, integrating, evaluating, and directing the work of project resource personnel at the professional, technical, and administrative work levels. Served as an Information Technology (IT) policy and planning expert on technical, analytical and advisory functions pertinent to development of local and enterprise IT policies, IT strategic plans, and the development of short and long range IT planning. Maintained liaison functions with manufacturers, professional organizations, and counterparts at other agencies and services regarding available products and emerging technologies and advancements. Accomplishments • Project lead for 119 Information Assurance and Interoperability systems tests over a four year span. Resulting in 88 systems receiving approval by the Defense Systems Acquisition Working Group (DSAWG) for placement on the Approved Products List (APL) • Restructured the NSA CryptoMod program for DISA by analyzing current program functions, devised efficient and effective processes and procedures; successfully executed the implementation plan. Resulted in reduction of manpower, increase in productivity and cost savings to customers on average of 10% per test event. • Recipient of the DISA Competitive Education Program stipend fund. Competed against over 100 highly capable individuals and was selected for a $13,000 education stipend for completion of Masters Degree.

title: Defense Red Switch Network Senior Telecommunications Systems Specialist
description: Performed supervisory customer service help desk/IT support duties and provided technical assistance to local functional users, to include General Officers and SES civilians, to minimize IT disruptions. Served as team leader for the complicated and specialized repair of IT equipment and circuits, through systematic troubleshooting, complex equipment reconditioning, re-engineering/modifying, and re-testing. Served as a senior IT specialist with responsibilities for developing, implementing, documenting and managing enterprise-wide communications and IT networks and associated IT systems in compliance with policies and guidelines. Resolved networking issues involving firewalls, routers, switches, and VOIP equipment. Accomplishments • Rewrote and implemented procedures for Enhanced Red Switch power supply checks. Directly resulting in improved accuracy of measurements and decrease in time needed to perform inspections. • Created and successfully implemented instructional pamphlet for Multifunctional Digital Adapter (MDA) software upgrade and PC interconnectivity to the MDA. Ensured reduced error in configuration of equipment and software settings for interconnectivity and critical upgrades to affected information systems.
