title: Electronic Warfare Systems Journeyman
description: 485th Intelligence Squadron, Mainz-Kastel, Germany (July, 2002 – April, 2005) 23rd Bomb Squadron, Minot AFB, North Dakota (May, 1999 – July, 2002) Electronic Warfare Systems Craftsman and Third Party Trainer Performed the role of first level supervisor with direct responsibility for eight IT and communications technicians. Responsibilities included supervising the troubleshooting, repair and maintenance for a wide variety of complex network infrastructure and satellite communications components. Additional duties included the role of knowledge based trainer with oversight for 23 junior technicians and the establishment of a technical training program that was capable of being tailored to non English speaking technicians at globally dispersed locations. Accomplishments • Selected as the National Security Agency Central Security Service, Europe, Non-Commissioned Officer Service Member of the Year for 2003 • United States Joint Service Commendation Medal recipient. Provided expert technical support and equipment training to United States and Global War on Terrorism partners. Fielded 5 platforms that ensured secure communications from coalition commanders to frontline war fighters. • United States Army Achievement Medal recipient. Provided expert technical support in the deployment of critical communications equipment, which resulted in enhanced readiness and capabilities of deployed units. • United States Air Force Achievement Medal recipient. Provided expert technical assistance to Boeing and Lockheed Martin engineers during electromagnetic compatibility testing.

title: Intelligence Officer
description: Over 7 years of Military Operations Intelligence experience. Responsible for the security and resource management for over 900 personnel. Utilized planning, analysis, and organizational skills to successfully execute combat missions in the Middle East area of responsibility. Skilled budget administrator managing multiple budgets across a wide spectrum of accounts. • Executive Officer for a group comprised of over 220 individuals providing personnel, logistical, operational, administrative, and maintenance support to over 4,500 military/ civilian personnel. • Developed and implemented operating guidance for the physical security of 2,000 weapons and sensitive items valued at over $1 million. 100% accuracy and zero discrepancies over 3-yr period. • Served as the principle security and intelligence advisor to a 900-person team responsible for protection of over 2,200 square miles in Iraq. • Initiated processes to overcome shortcomings in intelligence collection and analysis vital for the success of major operations in Iraq. • Planned and executed $600,000 annual budget. Developed and executed system that successfully managed over $10 million of property with zero negligent losses over a 2-yr period. • Instructor with several hundred hours of classroom experience. Trained all newly commissioned Army intelligence officers during one year tenure at U.S. Army Intelligence Center.

title: Director of Marketing and Funding Development
description: Promotion of U.S. post-secondary education institutions throughout China, Taiwan, Korea, Singapore, Hong Kong and beyond. AIEF conducts the highest quality U.S. education expositions in the East Asian Region, cooperating with the U.S. State Department Commercial Bureaus in Taipei, Seoul, Pusan, Beijing, Shanghai, Hong Kong and Singapore. Thousands of students have bridged from their East Asian homes to their U.S. higher educations through AIEF's uniquely tailored services.

title: Intelligence Analyst - Linguist
company: National Security Agency - Central Security Service
description: Intelligence detection, collection, transcription, analysis and reporting on the East Asian mainland. My last assignment was at NSA headquarters, Fort George G. Meade, Maryland, just north of Washington. It was a day of great pride when President Reagan dedicated our new offices in 1986. I was honored to receive the NSA's Joint Service Achievement Medal in the City of Washington, on 6 April, 1987. The citation reads: "Sergeant Dosemagen researched, analyzed, updated, and compiled vast amounts of information for inclusion in an ongoing, comprehensive and highly valuable technical publication. As a result of his dedication and in-depth research and analysis, he prepared for publication a substantive report of immense benefit within the intelligence community....."

title: Administrative/Project Assistant
description: Primary administrative assistant role: to maintain office operations at maximum efficiency to allow senior project managers to focus 100 % of their Door and Hardware Architecture expertise on projects at hand. • Performed the high demand multi-tasking necessary to prioritize, organize and complete tasks as the sole administrative staff member. • Managed general office operations; reception, correspondence (email, mail, UPS, FEDEX), calendar management, data entry, appointment scheduling, office supply management, file maintenance, fax and copy generation. • Served as liaison between general contractors (customers), and management. Secondary project assistant role: to perform specialized duties to assist senior project managers; order processing/tracking, invoicing, quote requests, submittals, contract review, bids, scheduling and project take-offs. • Responsible for all computer template and report design, maintenance and generation. • Maintained Federal Government paperwork procedures and security protocol. • Vetted by the National Security Agency Central Security Service for access to NSA/CSS facilities and official documents related to Federal Government job sites and projects. (Form G7608A)

title: SIGINT Analyst
description: SIGINT analyst in support of US Army South (ARSOUTH). Conduct extensive technical research and long term analysis on targets and areas of interest in the South and Central America AOR. Provide weekly products on key areas of interest to the ARSOUTH planners and senior leaders with enhanced situational awareness of transnational criminal organization activities. Complete requests for information (RFIs) submitted by other intelligence shops seeking additional information to clarify, verify or disprove reported information resulting in a more complete and accurate picture. All-source intelligence analyst in support of US Army North G2 Threat Fusion Center, responsible for providing accurate and comprehensive classified and open source analytical support. Receive and process numerous intelligence reports and messages to determine the significance and reliability of incoming information. Review intelligence information reports prior to their final review and release. Provide predictive, actionable foreign intelligence and counterintelligence, situational awareness, and early warning against all threats to USARNORTH's Area of Responsibility (AOR). Provide critical and timely intelligence analysis and evaluation for short and long-term deliverables focused on an array of issues, to include target capabilities and engagements. Provide deliverables on a deadline, to ensure that time critical intelligence information was distributed through the proper channels.

title: Counter Intelligence Analyst
description: Serve as a Counter Improvised Explosive Device (IED) and SIGINT analyst in support of Regional Command-East (RC-E), Afghanistan. Conduct extensive research for possible remote controlled IEDs and Remote FOB Trigger Type Devices identifying cells which pose a threat to Coalition Forces. Prepare, quality control, release and sanitize hundreds of tactical SIGINT reports daily that provide insight as well as key intelligence information to tactical commanders and coalition partners in the Afghanistan theater. Track division level targets of interest and summarize reporting for the different provinces within the RC-E AO for the daily reporting product.

title: Co-Founder & Chief Operations Officer
description: Cuspis Vir is Latin for "Point Man", it indicates the lead soldier who navigates a patrol group through uncertain and often hostile territory. Cuspis Vir provides consulting, leadership, coaching, training and mentoring program development and analysis. We work with individuals, families, groups and companies, providing support services to assist with successfully navigating and exploring the myriad of processes and procedures of finding and gaining access to much needed resources; from therapies to recreational to employment and self advocacy. Cuspis Vir educates and networks military and civilian families in Tampa Bay with available local, state and national level resources that provide relevant and timely training,therapies and services. As the COO for Cuspis Vir, I work with the military and civilian families, individuals and companies creating and implementing training, programs, family support and resiliency programs. Specializes in: Strategic Leadership ♦ Program Development ♦ Organizational Management ♦ Critical Analysis ♦ Coaching ♦ Teaching and Mentoring

title: Chairman, Walk Now for Autism Speaks Tampa Bay 2012, 2013, 2014
description: Current Chair of the Walk Now for Autism Speaks Tampa Bay signature fundraising and awareness event held annually in Tampa Bay. Walk event is April 11 2015 at the Tropicana Field. Co-Chair in 2013 and Logistics Chair in 2012. One of my proudest accomplishments has been facilitating substantial growth for the Walk Now for Autism Speaks events in the Tampa Bay Area. 3 years ago when I first volunteered with Autism Speaks our walk participation was less then 3,000 participants. I have helped facilitate, strengthen and furthered the connections between families, resources and community, business partners and other key supporters to increase the overall impact the Walk here in Tampa Bay. Our Walk in April 2014 had more than 9,000 participants, 40+ vendors and raised more than $300,000 to support much needed research, state/federal legislative advocacy and education/awareness programs for the families and our communities. Also active in: - Autism Speaks Community Grant Review, 2013, 2014 - Autism Speaks Grass Roots Advocacy Leader FL, 2014 - Autism Speaks Leadership 2014--Miami, FL - Autism Speaks Law Summit 2014--Nashville, TN Specializes in: Leadership ♦ Fundraising ♦ Program Growth ♦ Coaching ♦Organizational Networking ♦ Advocacy ♦ Public Speaking ♦ Education of issues ♦ Teamwork ♦ Collaboration ♦Event Coordination ♦ Awareness ♦ Project Management ♦ Mentoring ♦ Recruiting

title: Master Scheduler, Semiconductor Operations
description: Develops and maintains labor and equipment resource loading and other equipment capacity utilization for three production facilities. Applies statistical and analytical skills to gather data, analyze, quantify, and interpret significance in support of business decisions. Analyzes demand information, forecasts, sales orders, machine and labor capacity to provide loading information to senior management. Technical lead for four production planners. - SAP Super User - Developed a functional Excel template set for mapping almost 600 Oracle routings and 70 work centers. - As a leader of a team, we developed template models for all routings in Oracle and implemented these new routings in less than one month, saving $80,000 below the cost of a consultant-based solution. - Mapped Oracle routings over to SAP for over 1500 part numbers. - Created an method of Rough Cut Capacity Planning to level the plant's load and allow the plant's leadership to determine how to address potential limitations well before volume spikes arrive. - Put a canister conversion process into place that allowed the Chemical Vapor Deposition (CVD) division to go from $1 million over budget in capitalization to $400,000 under budget. First year alone re-purposed over 400 canisters, and have realized a cost avoidance of $1.5 million in the first three years.

title: US Army Major, MOS 35G-3W
description: As the Specialty Instruction Committee Chief for the US Army's Intelligence Center and School: responsible for the development and content for all Army officer training which was specific to the Army's intelligence disciplines (HUMINT, SIGINT, and IMINT). - Updated 80% of the Signals Intelligence course during a continuous rotation of instruction by implementing specific modules from class to class. - Converted portions of the courses to distance learning format, minimizing training costs of each student trained. -------------------------------------------------------- As a Signals Intelligence Staff Officer: Served as a member of the NSA's highly selective Junior Officer Cryptologic Career Program, whose purpose was to address issues throughout the agency that could not be resolved using normal processes or timelines. - One of only 5 officers selected for a liaison tour supporting CIA operations. - Managed a work center of over 400 personnel and $500 million of equipment. - Provided assessments and impact advice to senior military and civilian agency heads. -------------------------------------------------------- As a Company Commander: responsible for the training, health, welfare, and morale of 212 personnel, including 5 officers. - Improved the company’s status in every area measured during my term as commander. -------------------------------------------------------- As an Air Defense Artillery Battalion Intelligence Officer: provided intelligence for air threat to 3rd Armor division and missile threat to VII Corps during operations Desert Shield and Desert Storm. - Supervised one officer, four non-commissioned officers and three enlisted personnel. - Part of the team that developed a first-ever application of a tactical missile defense network protecting the US Army's VII corps with over 100,000 personnel in combat. - Scored a rare "Perfect" rating on quarterly inspections of the intelligence section's processes and procedures.

title: Cryptologic Resource Coordinator / Deputy Information Warfare Commander
description: Commander, Amphibious Squadron One Cryptologic Resource Coordinator (CRC) and Deputy Information Warfare Commander (DIWC) from 2009 to 2011. Deployed as Expeditionary Strike Group Five CRC from 2009-2010, exercising SIGINT operational tasking authority over 27 US and Allied cryptologic capable ships operating in the Arabian Gulf, Gulf of Aden, Somali Basin, and the Red Sea. Oversaw a groundbreaking SIGINT survey that leveraged Naval, national, and Allied assets that resulted in unprecedented access and yielded considerable insight into tactically-significant potential adversary signals. Earned designation as an Information Dominance Warfare Officer in 2010.

title: Deputy Chief
description: Cryptologic Support Group CENTCOM Deputy Chief and Operations Officer from 2005 to 2007. Led a 45-member Navy/Air Force/Marine Corps/Army team that provided sustained SIGINT support to Commander, US Central Command and oversaw the SIGINT activities of over 30 National Security Agency field sites in the CENTCOM Area of Responsibility in support of counter-terrorist operations. Spearheaded the effort that led to unprecedented access to NSA tools and databases to forward-deployed analysts providing target development in support of combat operations. Intelligence Oversight Manager for National Security Agency/Central Security Service Representative (NCR), US Central Command from 2005 to 2009. Provided executive management of all intelligence oversight activities for CSG CENTCOM and all NSA field sites under NCR CENTCOM’s authority. Initiated an unprecedented comprehensive program ensuring proper database auditing and intelligence oversight that ensured compliance with federal law and NSA policy while maintaining critical access of NSA databases by forward-deployed analysts supporting combat operations.

title: Ship Cryptologic Officer
description: USS CONSTELLATION Cryptologic Officer and Shipboard Signals Exploitation Space Division Officer from 2002 to2003. Managed a diverse Navy, Marine Corp, Australian, and Canadian team in the collection of adversary signals intelligence in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom and Operation Enduring Freedom, providing daily threat/target briefings to EA-6B Prowler flight crews and setting an unprecedented standard of collection success for an aircraft carrier. As Command Security Manager, oversaw the destruction, disposal, and disposition of all classified material on board prior to decommissioning.

title: Avionics Technician / Maintenance Manager
description: Twice deployed on board USS RANGER from 1990-1993 as part of the Aircraft Intermediate Maintenance Department (AIMD) F-14 AWG-9 Radar Workcenter in support of Operation Desert Shield, Desert Storm, Southern Watch, and Restore Hope. As night-shift supervisor, supervised 7 technicians in component-level troubleshooting and micro-miniature repair in support of high-tempo combat operations. Designated an AIMD collateral duty inspector tasked with performing quality-assurance oversight over all maintenance activities within the workcenter. Production Supervisor, Naval Air Station Miramar Aircraft Intermediate Maintenance Department (AIMD) F-14 AWG-9 Radar Workcenter, 1993-1996. Managed the maintenance efforts of 80 military and civilian technicians across three work shifts. Directed streamlined maintenance procedures and aggressive material cannibalization to reduce maintenance backlog to an historic low and eliminate all "expeditious repair" items from backlog. Developed excellent working relationships with other local maintenance activities and leveraged personal contacts to engineer dynamic collaborative responses to unexpected test station outages and maintain delivery of "Ready For Issue" components in support of F-14 flight operations. Expertise in quality assurance and in-depth understanding of the maintenance process led to designations as both a collateral duty inspector qualifier and a Naval Aviation Maintenance Program qualifier.

title: Program Manager
description: In support of the Human Terrain System (HTS) provide program support to 35+ forward deployed team members comprised of Social Scientists, Research Managers, Human Terrain Analysts and Linguists. Responsible for all aspects of the daily management of the contract. Responsible for billing of nearly $1M per month. On a monthly basis, reconciled more than 70 timecards, paychecks, travel vouchers, commercial contract expenditures for lodging and rental cars, business credit cards bills, paychecks, and travel arrangements. Developed a cradle to grave personnel tracking system to ensure new employees were properly assimilated into the company. Work hand in hand with the customer's Program Manager in order to ensure the highest quality candidates were provided to the customer. As CLI Solutions continued to grow, in addition to the Human Terrain System, also assumed the Program Manager position for the USCENTCOM Afghanistan/Pakistan Center of Excellence and the INSCOM Global Linguist Related Support contract. In collaboration with the company's General Manager, executed a complete overhaul of the company benefits package including source selection, benefit limits and employee education.

title: Program Management
description: In support of the Office of Weapons & Space at the NSA, provide program management support. Provide daily support to the Program Management Office (PMO) for ELINT Modernization within NSA. Maintain agenda and tracking of action items, both open and closed. Maintain and update the Monthly Program Review (MPR) for customer briefing. Manage monthly billable hours, update monthly financial reports, developed "New Employee" checklist and set up workstations. Manage a funding cite in excess of $900K used to fund training and conferences for the entire Weapons & Space directorate at NSA. Coordinate with each work center supervisor to provide FY04 spend plans, future training requirements and liaison for importing external training from the University of Tennessee and Georgia Tech. Provide conference support, logistics and travel arrangements.

title: Deputy Program Manager
description: Responsible for tracking all deliverables on a contract in support of K52 at the NSA. Task Senior Scientists, Engineers, Software Developers, Signals Analysts, Logisticians, and Trainers to provide weekly, monthly and quarterly inputs for submission as contract deliverables. Compile all inputs into briefs and submit to the COR (Contracting Officer's Representative). Provide Self Evaluation Report to the Government for award fee determination. Responsible for contract security issues as they relate to deliverables. Program Cost Analyst - Solely responsible for a yearly contract budget in excess of $13M. Provide the daily management of labor costs, travel, facility costs, and material purchases. Function as the liaison between SAIC and seven subcontract companies on all matters concerning labor distribution, award fees, and monthly invoices. Coordinate with and provide budgetary data to accounting personnel, ensuring on time delivery of the monthly FMER (Funds, Manpower Expenditures Report) to the Government. Input timecard hours into Quicken, run reports necessary to update the program budget. Procurement - Purchase all materials necessary in the fulfillment of the contract. Interface with numerous vendors to provide the most cost effective merchandise. Input all PR's (Purchase Requests) into SAP. Receipt for materials as they are delivered. Coordinate and track all purchases through the COR. Misc: Do monthly CMS updates/destruction. Function as backup for travel, escorts, document security, meeting support, pagers, red phones and GFE.

title: CNO Directed Command Master Chief
description: The highest enlisted position within the Naval Security Group. Responsible for maintaining liaison with over 13,000 Cryptologic and Electronic Warfare enlisted Sailors and their families. Sole enlisted advisor to a two star Admiral on issues dealing with quality of life and morale. Member of the Master Chief Petty Officer of the Navy (MCPON)/Chief of Naval Operations (CNO) Advisory Panel. Member of the Central Security Service Enlisted Leadership Conference Committee (CSSELC) which includes the Senior Enlisted Advisors (SEA) of each Service Cryptologic Element. Recommendations and reports go directly to DIRNSA (DIRECTOR, NSA). As a member of the MCPON/CNO Advisory panel, participated in semi-annual conferences to work key issues involving enlisted Sailors. Regularly called on by the MCPON to work local Naval District Washington (NDW) issues on his behalf. Personally selected by Assistant Chief for Education, Training and Personnel to serve as key member of special equal opportunity, sexual harassment assessment team. Developed the first "Chief's Talk", a Chief Petty Officer (CPO) newsletter to over 800 CT and EW CPOs'. Newsletter provided leadership training and guidance. Traveled extensively throughout the CNSG claimancy stateside and remote locations overseas, conducting "White Hat" and "CPO" calls as a means of providing policy guidance and information exchange.

title: Bureau of Naval Personnel
description: Rating Technical Advisor for CTO Community (TECHAD) - BUPERS 221N - Responsible for "Cradle to grave" rating management of community health & welfare issues for a 2000 person rating. Determined impact of CNO personnel policy on rating; advised, recommended policy adjustments impacting rating and Navy personnel overall. Initiated accession goals. Determined "A" & "C" school requirements, advancement targets, and women in the Navy goals. Advised the rating primary advisor and resource sponsor on NEC and billet alignment matters. Screened a myriad of requests for entry/exit from rating (lateral conversions, Fleet Reserves Request, High Year Tenure, early outs, etc.). title: Program Manager
description: In support of the Human Terrain System (HTS) provide program support to 35+ forward deployed team members comprised of Social Scientists, Research Managers, Human Terrain Analysts and Linguists. Responsible for all aspects of the daily management of the contract. Responsible for billing of nearly $1M per month. On a monthly basis, reconciled more than 70 timecards, paychecks, travel vouchers, commercial contract expenditures for lodging and rental cars, business credit cards bills, paychecks, and travel arrangements. Developed a cradle to grave personnel tracking system to ensure new employees were properly assimilated into the company. Work hand in hand with the customer's Program Manager in order to ensure the highest quality candidates were provided to the customer. As CLI Solutions continued to grow, in addition to the Human Terrain System, also assumed the Program Manager position for the USCENTCOM Afghanistan/Pakistan Center of Excellence and the INSCOM Global Linguist Related Support contract. In collaboration with the company's General Manager, executed a complete overhaul of the company benefits package including source selection, benefit limits and employee education.

title: Deputy Program Manager
description: Responsible for tracking all deliverables on a contract in support of K52 at the NSA. Task Senior Scientists, Engineers, Software Developers, Signals Analysts, Logisticians, and Trainers to provide weekly, monthly and quarterly inputs for submission as contract deliverables. Compile all inputs into briefs and submit to the COR (Contracting Officer's Representative). Provide Self Evaluation Report to the Government for award fee determination. Responsible for contract security issues as they relate to deliverables. Program Cost Analyst - Solely responsible for a yearly contract budget in excess of $13M. Provide the daily management of labor costs, travel, facility costs, and material purchases. Function as the liaison between SAIC and seven subcontract companies on all matters concerning labor distribution, award fees, and monthly invoices. Coordinate with and provide budgetary data to accounting personnel, ensuring on time delivery of the monthly FMER (Funds, Manpower Expenditures Report) to the Government. Input timecard hours into Quicken, run reports necessary to update the program budget. Procurement - Purchase all materials necessary in the fulfillment of the contract. Interface with numerous vendors to provide the most cost effective merchandise. Input all PR's (Purchase Requests) into SAP. Receipt for materials as they are delivered. Coordinate and track all purchases through the COR. Misc: Do monthly CMS updates/destruction. Function as backup for travel, escorts, document security, meeting support, pagers, red phones and GFE.

title: CNO Directed Command Master Chief
description: The highest enlisted position within the Naval Security Group. Responsible for maintaining liaison with over 13,000 Cryptologic and Electronic Warfare enlisted Sailors and their families. Sole enlisted advisor to a two star Admiral on issues dealing with quality of life and morale. Member of the Master Chief Petty Officer of the Navy (MCPON)/Chief of Naval Operations (CNO) Advisory Panel. Member of the Central Security Service Enlisted Leadership Conference Committee (CSSELC) which includes the Senior Enlisted Advisors (SEA) of each Service Cryptologic Element. Recommendations and reports go directly to DIRNSA (DIRECTOR, NSA). As a member of the MCPON/CNO Advisory panel, participated in semi-annual conferences to work key issues involving enlisted Sailors. Regularly called on by the MCPON to work local Naval District Washington (NDW) issues on his behalf. Personally selected by Assistant Chief for Education, Training and Personnel to serve as key member of special equal opportunity, sexual harassment assessment team. Developed the first "Chief's Talk", a Chief Petty Officer (CPO) newsletter to over 800 CT and EW CPOs'. Newsletter provided leadership training and guidance. Traveled extensively throughout the CNSG claimancy stateside and remote locations overseas, conducting "White Hat" and "CPO" calls as a means of providing policy guidance and information exchange.

title: Bureau of Naval Personnel
description: Rating Technical Advisor for CTO Community (TECHAD) - BUPERS 221N - Responsible for "Cradle to grave" rating management of community health & welfare issues for a 2000 person rating. Determined impact of CNO personnel policy on rating; advised, recommended policy adjustments impacting rating and Navy personnel overall. Initiated accession goals. Determined "A" & "C" school requirements, advancement targets, and women in the Navy goals. Advised the rating primary advisor and resource sponsor on NEC and billet alignment matters. Screened a myriad of requests for entry/exit from rating (lateral conversions, Fleet Reserves Request, High Year Tenure, early outs, etc.). Advised the Enlisted Community Manager (ECM) on all career planning, special programs (SRB, EB, VSI/SSB, and TERA) and other rating issues.

title: CTO/CTA Training Branch Head
description: Responsible for all aspects of training for 3,450 personnel within the CTO and CTA ratings. Acted as Chairperson of the "CTO of the Future" Flag level advisory group. Was the lead architect in the major community training realignments to pace future technology and mission growth and readiness. Acted as the chairperson for the NSA sponsored Cryptologic Element, Automated Information System (AIS) training committee, providing conscientious and astute coordination to ensure complete implementation of complex mission objectives.
